<synonym datatype='string'>OP00046</synonym>
<synonym datatype='string'>lexA</synonym>
<comment datatype='string'>Two known and one putative LexA transcription factor binding sites (TFBS) were identified in the regulatory region of the lexAp promoter [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7027255&quot;&gt;Little81&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7027256&quot;&gt;Brent81&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8057377&quot;&gt;Lewis94&lt;/a&gt;]. Recently, it was demonstrated that the putative TFBS, located 50 bp upstream of the transcriptional start site of &lt;i&gt;lexA&lt;/i&gt;p, is nonfunctional; therefore, it was removed from this database, leaving only two TFBSs regulating &lt;i&gt;lexA-dinF&lt;/i&gt; expression, although apparently only one of these sites would be sufficient to cause repression of &lt;i&gt;lexA&lt;/i&gt;p [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/32817380&quot;&gt;Kozuch20&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
Upstream of the &lt;i&gt;lexA&lt;/i&gt; gene there is a site for dynamic methylation that is methylated during stationary phase [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34849799&quot;&gt;Lewis22&lt;/a&gt;]. Although this methylation site overlaps with a LexA binding site, it does not affect the regulation by LexA, [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34849799&quot;&gt;Lewis22&lt;/a&gt;]. However, binding of LexA to DNA diminishes the methylation of that site [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/34849799&quot;&gt;Lewis22&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>
